com.samsung.android.sdk.healthdata

Interface HealthConstants.Exercise

  • All Superinterfaces:
    HealthConstants.Common, HealthConstants.SessionMeasurement
    Enclosing class:
    HealthConstants

    public static interface HealthConstants.Exercise
extends HealthConstants.SessionMeasurement
    This interface defines exercise data of user.

    Properties of the following extending interfaces are available for this data type.

    • HealthConstants.Common
    • HealthConstants.SessionMeasurement

    Converting Data to Compressed JSON

    LIVE_DATA and LOCATION_DATA of exercise data are defined as the compressed JSON format.
    Compress exercise data for saving exercise data to S Health. 

       public class ExerciseExample {

     public class LiveData {
         long start_time = 0L;
         float heart_rate = 0.f;
         float cadence = 0.f;
         float count = 0.f;
         float power = 0.f;
         float speed = 0.f;
     }

     public byte[] getCompressedJson(ArrayList<LiveData> liveData) throws IOException {
         // convert data class to JSON string
         Gson gson = new Gson();
         String jsonStr = gson.toJson(liveData);

         // compress JSON
         ByteArrayOutputStream bos = new ByteArrayOutputStream(jsonStr.length());
         GZIPOutputStream gos = new GZIPOutputStream(bos);
         gos.write(jsonStr.getBytes());
         gos.close();
         byte[] zip = bos.toByteArray();
         bos.close();

         return zip;
     }
 }

    Getting Data from Compressed JSON

    Exercise data's LIVE_DATA and LOCATION_DATA are saved with the compressed JSON format.
    You can read detailed information of exercise data after decompressing them. 

       public class ExerciseExample {

     public class LiveData {
         long start_time = 0L;
         float heart_rate = 0.f;
         float cadence = 0.f;
         float count = 0.f;
         float power = 0.f;
         float speed = 0.f;
     }

     public ArrayList<LiveData> getLiveData(byte[] zip) throws IOException, JsonSyntaxException {
         // decompress ZIP
         final int BUFFER_SIZE = 1024*1000;
         ByteArrayInputStream bis = new ByteArrayInputStream(zip);
         GZIPInputStream gis = new GZIPInputStream(bis, BUFFER_SIZE);
         StringBuilder jsonBuilder = new StringBuilder();
         byte[] data = new byte[BUFFER_SIZE];
         int bytesRead;
         while ((bytesRead = gis.read(data)) != -1) {
             jsonBuilder.append(new String(data, 0, bytesRead));
         }
         gis.close();
         bis.close();

         // translate JSON string to data class
         ArrayList<LiveData> liveData = new ArrayList<LiveData>();
         Gson gson = new Gson();
         liveData = gson.fromJson(jsonBuilder.toString(), new TypeToken<List<LiveData>>() {}.getType());
         return liveData;
     }
 }

    Properties

    Exercise data has the following properties.
    See more common properties by spreading this section out.

      Property name Description
      HealthConstants.Exercise.UUID [Mandatory]
      Data's unique ID,
      assigned by the system when new data is inserted
      HealthConstants.Exercise.CREATE_TIME [Mandatory]
      Data's created time in the health data store,
      assigned by the system when new data is inserted
      HealthConstants.Exercise.UPDATE_TIME [Mandatory]
      Data's updated time in the health data store,
      assigned by the system when new data is updated
      HealthConstants.Exercise.PACKAGE_NAME [Mandatory]
      Application package name which provides data,
      assigned by the system when new data is inserted
      HealthConstants.Exercise.DEVICE_UUID [Mandatory]
      Device identifier of the source device which provides health data
      HealthConstants.Exercise.START_TIME [Mandatory]
      UTC Time when the measurement is started
      HealthConstants.Exercise.END_TIME [Mandatory]
      UTC Time after the measurement has ended

      If the S Health's exercise data has the same START_TIME and END_TIME,
      it means the user didn't select the "PAUSE" or "STOP" button yet on S Health.

      HealthConstants.Exercise.TIME_OFFSET [Mandatory]
      Time offset which considers time zone and daylight saving time

      • EXERCISE_TYPE

        static final String EXERCISE_TYPE
        Predefined exercise type.
        Your application's exercise data is shown on S Health if the data sets this value.

        If you cannot find a proper exercise type in predefined types, set the value as 0 and set EXERCISE_CUSTOM_TYPE instead of it.

        • Optional
        • Type: int
        • Available values: predefined types

        Since:
        1.0.0
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • EXERCISE_CUSTOM_TYPE

        static final String EXERCISE_CUSTOM_TYPE
        Custom exercise type. Define its value as FQDN, e.g. "com.yourcompany.exercise.type.exercise_name".

        This property has to be used only when you cannot find a required exercise type in predefined types. If this custom type is used, set the value of EXERCISE_TYPE as 0. Your custom health data is inserted to the health data store but it is not shown in S Health.

        • Optional
        • Type: String
        • Value length: 1 ~ 255

        Since:
        1.0.0

      • LIVE_DATA

        static final String LIVE_DATA
        Live data (e.g. heart rate, speed, power, and so on) during exercise which is compressed with the JSON format.

        • Optional
        • Type: byte[]
        • Maximum data size: 1000 KB

        Live data can have one or more segments.
        E.g. S Health starts the exercise data record when the user starts a specified exercise. It makes several segments to live data for each specific period. When the user tabs the 'stop' button finally it finishes the exercise data record.

        Each segment is composed of the following JSON keys.

        JSON key Type Mandatory
        "start_time" long Yes
        "heart_rate" float No
        "cadence" float No
        "count" int No
        "power" float No
        "speed" float No
        "distance" float No

        The following example shows the JSON format for LIVE_DATA. 

           {
     "start_time":1422457096536,
     "heart_rate":147.48181,
     "cadence":95.84712,
     "count":83,
     "power":99.50436,
     "speed":11.061617,
     "distance":250
 }

        Especially, each segment's "count" and "distance" in live data are accumulated values to the each segment's "start_time"unlike other values such as "heart_rate" and "cadence" that indicate the measured value at the point of each segment's "start_time".

        Its use cases are:

        • Converting data to compressed JSON
        • Getting data from compressed JSON

        Since:
        1.0.0
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • LOCATION_DATA

        static final String LOCATION_DATA
        Location (trajectory) data during exercise which is compressed with the JSON format.
        It follows WGS 84.

        • Optional
        • Type: byte[]
        • Maximum data size: 1000 KB

        Location data can have one or more segment.
        Each segment is composed of the following JSON Keys.

        JSON key Type Mandatory
        "start_time" long Yes
        "latitude" float No
        "longitude" float No
        "altitude" float No
        "accuracy" float No

        The following example shows the JSON format for LOCATION_DATA 

           {
     "start_time":1422457096536,
     "latitude":2.7413864,
     "longitude":60.37224,
     "altitude":39.0,
     "accuracy":0.0
 }

        Its use cases are:

        • Converting data to compressed JSON
        • Getting data from compressed JSON

        Since:
        1.0.0
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values
